<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-220-306  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 220 306.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  April 24 1989 v216 n17 p8(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DOJ hits Greene's legal standards. (Department of Justice; USDistrict Judge Harold Greene) (News of the Week)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mason, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US Department of Justice (DOJ) challenges US District Court JudgeHarold Greene's authority under the antitrust settlement withATandamp;T.andP;  The DOJ asks a federal appeals court to correct Greene's'erroneous legal standard.' Referring to the Modified FinalJudgement (MFJ), DOJ contends Greene has 'ventured far afield ofthe precise competition standards mandated by the decree' and has'failed to respect the limits' of his jurisdiction.andP;  Furtherallegations stipulate that Greene has asserted a right to considerfactors that involve public policy issues besides the effect ofcompetition.andP;  The DOJ contends antitrust laws do not afford thedistrict court a general mandate to undertake regulation infurtherance of other public policies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone companiesUnited States. Department of JusticeGovernment RegulationTelecommunicationsAntitrust Laws.andO;Person:    Greene, Harold (telecommunication policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>